# Git Commits

## Logical chunks

Split work into **separate commits** when changes serve different purposes. One commit = one logical unit of work.

- **Do** group: one feature, one bug fix, one refactor, one migration, or one config change
- **Don't** mix unrelated changes (e.g. feature + unrelated style fix + dependency bump in one commit)
- **Order** commits so each builds on the last (schema/migrations before code that depends on them)

When multiple logical chunks exist in the working tree, make **multiple commits** — stage and commit each chunk separately.

## Push after commit

**Always push** after a successful commit:

```bash
git push
```

If the branch has no upstream yet:

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
```

Do not leave commits only on local without pushing unless the user explicitly asks not to push.

## Only commit when asked

Create commits only when the user explicitly requests it. If unclear, ask first.
